---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';
import Sample from '../../components/Sample.astro';
---
<Base title="Time Is A Design Material" section={2}>
  <article class="prose">

    <SectionHeader
      n={2}
      title="Time Is A Design Material"
      meta="~600 words · 2 interactive samples"
    />

    <p>
      Language models come in two modes, and both make the same design
      argument. Standard models produce tokens in a single continuous pass
      — no separate thinking phase, just output arriving one token at a
      time. Reasoning models do something closer to what the word implies:
      they work through a problem first, then speak. In both cases,
      streaming that process to the user — word by word, thought by thought
      — is technically straightforward. What's interesting is that it's
      also the right design choice, for reasons that have nothing to do
      with latency.
    </p>

    <p>
      A response that arrives all at once, fully formed, feels like it was
      retrieved from a database rather than reasoned through. The instant
      appearance of five paragraphs triggers a "this was cached" instinct,
      even when it wasn't. Streaming changes this. And with reasoning
      models, the argument grows stronger still: watching a model work
      through a problem in real time — weighing, backtracking, arriving —
      is the closest computing has come to making thought visible. The
      experience shifts from retrieving an answer to watching one form.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      Streaming text isn't a technical limitation — it's a design choice
      that mimics thinking-as-writing. An instant dump would feel cheaper
      even if it were faster.
    </PullQuote>

    <Sample label="Interactive sample — streaming cadence">
      <div style="font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif;">
        <div id="s2-stream-output" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.85; color: #4a3728; min-height: 72px; margin-bottom: 16px;"></div>
        <div style="display: flex; gap: 8px; align-items: center;">
          <button
            id="s2-play-btn"
            onclick="s2StartStream()"
            style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; background: #fdf3e8; border: 0.5px solid #e8c9a0; color: #8b6345; border-radius: 6px; padding: 6px 14px; cursor: pointer; transition: background 120ms;"
          >▶ Play</button>
          <span id="s2-speed-label" style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; color: #a08060;">~25 tokens/sec</span>
          <input
            id="s2-speed"
            type="range"
            min="10"
            max="120"
            value="90"
            oninput="(function(el){ const delay = 130 - parseInt(el.value, 10); document.getElementById('s2-speed-label').textContent = '~' + Math.round(1000/delay) + ' tokens/sec'; })(this)"
            style="accent-color: #c9956a; flex: 1; max-width: 120px;"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
      <script>
        (function() {
          const text = "The interface that earns its invisibility leaves no seam between intention and execution. You think the thought, and the thought is already on the page.";
          function s2StartStream() {
            const out = document.getElementById('s2-stream-output');
            const btn = document.getElementById('s2-play-btn');
            const speed = document.getElementById('s2-speed');
            if (!out || !btn || !speed) return;
            out.textContent = '';
            btn.disabled = true;
            btn.textContent = '…';
            let i = 0;
            const delay = 130 - parseInt(speed.value, 10);
            const iv = setInterval(() => {
              out.textContent += text[i];
              i++;
              if (i >= text.length) {
                clearInterval(iv);
                btn.disabled = false;
                btn.textContent = '▶ Play';
              }
            }, delay);
          }
          window.s2StartStream = s2StartStream;
        })();
      </script>
    </Sample>

    <h2>Duration as design token</h2>

    <p>
      If streaming makes time visible, easing curves make time <em>feel</em> intentional.
      The difference between a UI that feels mechanical and one that feels alive
      is almost always in the transition curves — not the transitions themselves.
      A 240ms fade with a linear curve feels like a toggle. The same 240ms with
      <code>cubic-bezier(.4, 0, .2, 1)</code> feels like breathing.
    </p>

    <p>
      This matters enough to encode in design tokens. When easing lives in a
      CSS variable, it's a named decision, not a number someone typed once and
      never revisited. <code>--ease-soft</code> communicates intent.
      <code>cubic-bezier(.4, 0, .2, 1)</code> communicates nothing.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="Duration tokens">
      Duration tokens for this system: <code>--dur-fast: 120ms</code> for
      micro-interactions (hover reveals, button presses);
      <code>--dur-base: 240ms</code> for state transitions;
      <code>--dur-slow: 480ms</code> for page enters and large reveals;
      <code>--dur-crawl: 800ms</code> for the streaming cadence demo above.
    </Annotation>

    <Sample label="Interactive sample — ease comparison">
      <div style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; color: #4a3728;">
        <div style="margin-bottom: 16px; color: #a08060; font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: 0.04em;">Click a row to animate. Same duration — different feel.</div>

        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px;">
          <!-- Linear -->
          <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: center;">
            <div style="width: 80px; font-size: 11px; color: #a08060; text-align: right; font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;">linear</div>
            <div style="flex: 1; height: 36px; background: #f7f0e6; border-radius: 6px; position: relative; cursor: pointer; overflow: hidden;" onclick="s2Animate(this, 'linear')">
              <div style="position:absolute; top: 6px; left: 6px; width: 24px; height: 24px; background: #c9956a; border-radius: 4px; transition: transform 600ms linear;" class="s2-ball"></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- ease (browser default) -->
          <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: center;">
            <div style="width: 80px; font-size: 11px; color: #a08060; text-align: right; font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;">ease</div>
            <div style="flex: 1; height: 36px; background: #f7f0e6; border-radius: 6px; position: relative; cursor: pointer; overflow: hidden;" onclick="s2Animate(this, 'ease')">
              <div style="position:absolute; top: 6px; left: 6px; width: 24px; height: 24px; background: #c9956a; border-radius: 4px; transition: transform 600ms ease;" class="s2-ball"></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- ease-soft (our token) -->
          <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: center;">
            <div style="width: 80px; font-size: 11px; color: #8b6345; text-align: right; font-weight: 500; font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;">--ease-soft</div>
            <div style="flex: 1; height: 36px; background: #fdf3e8; border: 0.5px solid #e8c9a0; border-radius: 6px; position: relative; cursor: pointer; overflow: hidden;" onclick="s2Animate(this, 'cubic-bezier(.4,0,.2,1)')">
              <div style="position:absolute; top: 6px; left: 6px; width: 24px; height: 24px; background: #b07d5c; border-radius: 4px; transition: transform 600ms cubic-bezier(.4,0,.2,1);" class="s2-ball"></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <script>
        (function() {
          function s2Animate(track, ease) {
            const ball = track.querySelector('.s2-ball');
            if (!ball) return;
            const trackW = track.offsetWidth;
            const ballW = 24;
            const maxX = trackW - ballW - 12;
            const isRight = ball.style.transform === '' || ball.style.transform === 'translateX(0px)' || !ball.style.transform;
            ball.style.transition = `transform 600ms ${ease}`;
            ball.style.transform = isRight ? `translateX(${maxX}px)` : 'translateX(0px)';
          }
          window.s2Animate = s2Animate;
        })();
      </script>
    </Sample>

    <p>
      The third row doesn't look radically different from the second. But run
      them side by side enough times and a preference emerges — not as an
      aesthetic opinion, but as a physiological response. The soft ease matches
      the deceleration curve of physical objects. The browser's default
      <code>ease</code> does not. Over thousands of micro-interactions, this
      accumulates into the difference between a UI that feels mechanical and one
      that feels inhabited.
    </p>

  </article>
</Base>
